'generate_query[1].predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Acratopotes | In Greek mythology, Acratopotes (Greek: Ἀκρατοπότης ), the drinker of unmixed wine, was a hero worshiped in Munychia in Attica. According to Pausanias, who calls him simply Acratus, he was one of the divine companions of Dionysus, who was worshiped at Attica. Pausanias saw his image at Athens in the house of Polytion, where it was fixed in the wall.', 'Ascolia | Ascolia, in Ancient Greece, was a yearly feast that the peasants of Attica celebrated in honor of Dionysus. The rites included sacrificing a goat, chosen because goats were prone to eating and destroying grapevines, and using its skin to make a football, which was filled with wine and smeared in oil. Festival participants then competed against each other by trying to leap onto it in a game that gave the festival its name ("askoliazein" or "ασκωλιάζειν"); the one who remained standing at the end of the contest won the wineskin as a prize. Participants also painted their faces with wine dregs, sang hymns, and recited satirical poetry.', 'Dionysus Cup | The Dionysus Cup is the modern name for one of the best known works of ancient Greek vase painting, a "kylix" (drinking cup) dating to 540–530 BC. It is one of the masterpieces of the Attic Black-figure potter Exekias and one of the most significant works in the Staatliche Antikensammlungen in Munich.'], 'question': 'What drink would the people of Nannus use to celebrate what Dionysus did for them?', 'reasoning': 'The context does not provide specific information about the people of Nannus or a direct celebration related to Dionysus. However, the context mentions that Acratopotes, a hero worshiped in Munychia, was one of the divine companions of Dionysus, and that the people of Attica celebrated Ascolia, a festival in honor of Dionysus, by playing a game with a wine-filled goat skin. Therefore, it is reasonable to infer that the people of Nannus, if they were in 